### Customize Theme with @theme Directive in CSS

Source: https://tailwindcss.com/docs/adding-custom-styles

Use the @theme directive to customize design tokens like color palettes, spacing scales, typography, breakpoints, and easing functions. This approach allows centralized management of design system variables that can be referenced throughout your Tailwind project.

```css
@theme {
  --font-display: "Satoshi", "sans-serif";
  --breakpoint-3xl: 120rem;
  --color-avocado-100: oklch(0.99 0 0);
  --color-avocado-200: oklch(0.98 0.04 113.22);
  --color-avocado-300: oklch(0.94 0.11 115.03);
  --color-avocado-400: oklch(0.92 0.19 114.08);
  --color-avocado-500: oklch(0.84 0.18 117.33);
  --color-avocado-600: oklch(0.53 0.12 118.34);
  --ease-fluid: cubic-bezier(0.3, 0, 0, 1);
  --ease-snappy: cubic-bezier(0.2, 0, 0, 1);
}
```

--------------------------------

### Define Custom Color Theme Variable in Tailwind CSS

Source: https://tailwindcss.com/docs/theme

This CSS snippet demonstrates how to define a new custom color, `--color-mint-500`, using Tailwind's `@theme` directive. This makes `bg-mint-500`, `text-mint-500`, and `fill-mint-500` utility classes available for use in HTML.

```css
@import "tailwindcss";@theme {  --color-mint-500: oklch(0.72 0.11 178);}
```

--------------------------------

### Add Custom Colors with @theme Directive

Source: https://tailwindcss.com/docs/colors

Define custom colors using @theme to add new color utilities to your project under the --color-* namespace. Custom colors become available as utility classes like bg-midnight and text-tahiti.

```css
@import "tailwindcss";
@theme {
  --color-midnight: #121063;
  --color-tahiti: #3ab7bf;
  --color-bermuda: #78dcca;
}
```

--------------------------------

### Configure a Custom Tailwind CSS Theme with Initial Variables

Source: https://tailwindcss.com/docs/theme

This snippet demonstrates how to completely disable the default Tailwind CSS theme by setting the global theme variable namespace to `initial` within the `@theme` block in `app.css`. This ensures that only custom values are used, making utility classes available only for the defined custom theme variables like `font-body` and `text-dusk`.

```css
@import "tailwindcss";@theme {  --*: initial;  --spacing: 4px;  --font-body: Inter, sans-serif;  --color-lagoon: oklch(0.72 0.11 221.19);  --color-coral: oklch(0.74 0.17 40.24);  --color-driftwood: oklch(0.79 0.06 74.59);  --color-tide: oklch(0.49 0.08 205.88);  --color-dusk: oklch(0.82 0.15 72.09);}
```

### Core concepts > Functions and directives > Directives > @theme

Source: https://tailwindcss.com/docs/functions-and-directives

The `@theme` directive is used to define your project's custom design tokens, such as fonts, colors, breakpoints, and easing functions. This centralizes your design system configuration and makes it available throughout your Tailwind project. You can learn more about customizing your theme in the theme variables documentation.

